<subSubSection id="F7D86578FFAA1B1DFE23FE6B002A4447" pageId="20" pageNumber="170" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="BF7D36F3FFAA1B1DFE23FE6B002A4447" blockId="20.[441,1838,375,625]" pageId="20" pageNumber="170">
This species is widely distributed in the Pacific. In Hawaii it has been known as 
<emphasis id="8DB6EAE1FFAA1B1DFDABFDA604B3440B" box="[625,949,531,573]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="170">
<taxonomicName id="78C24D70FFAA1B1DFDABFDA604B6440B" authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1878" box="[625,944,531,573]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ceresium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="170" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simplex">Ceresium simplex</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
We found it very abundant in 1936, breeding in dead branches or fallen trees of several kinds. The beetles often came to light.
</paragraph>
